ch Andre, Armand, Emile, Andree, Jean Pierre, Laurent, Monique, Ovide, Pierre, Remi, Yvon.","French (northern): variant of <b>Coillard</b>, from Old French <i>coillard</i> ‘uncastrated animal, ram’, used as a nickname for a rakish, libidinous individual.","History: The surname <i>Couillard</i> was first brought to North America by Guillaume Couillard from Saint-Servan-sur-Mer in Ille-et-Vilaine, Brittany (France), who was in QC by 1621. His descendants also bear the surname <i>Després</i> (see   Despres  )."]},{"name":"Dupre","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Antoine, Jacques, Alcee, Andre, Armand, Camille, Lucien, Pierre, Adrien, Albertine, Alcide.","French (<b>Dupré</b>): topographic name from <i>pré</i> ‘meadow’ (from Old French <i>pred</i>), with fused preposition and definite article <i>du</i> ‘from the’; or a habitational name for someone from any of several places in various parts of France named Le Pré. Compare   Deupree   and   Dupree  .","History: This surname is listed (in the form <i>Du Pré</i>) in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina. — In North America, this surname was originally also part of a title. It was Louis Lecomte, <i>sieur</i> Dupré, from Pouzauges in Vendée, France, whose title <i>sieur Dupré</i> became the surname <i>Dupré</i>. He married Catherine Rolland de St. Georges in Montreal, QC, in 1683. His descendants also bear the surname   Terrebonne  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Gauthier","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>Walter</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Gauthier Desprest de Quiévrain was born in 1176, in Europe. He had at least 1 son with Isabeau de Mortagne de Tournai. He died about 1243, at the age of 68."},"et":{"in 1176–vers 1243":"1176–umbes 1243","1176–Female":"1176–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1176–1243":"1176–1243","ABT 1230":"umbes 1230","in 1176":"1176","1243":"1243","1176":"1176","1230":"1230","vers 1243":"umbes 1243","Europa":"Europe"},"fi":{"in 1176–vers 1243":"1176–noin 1243","1176–Female":"1176–Kuollut","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1176–1243":"1176–1243","ABT 1230":"noin 1230","in 1176":"1176","1243":"1243","1176":"1176","1230":"1230","vers 1243":"noin 1243","Europa":"Europe"},"fr":{"in 1176–vers 1243":"1176–environ 1243","1176–Female":"1176–Décédée","1230–Male":"1230–Décédé","1176–1243":"1176–1243","ABT 1230":"environ 1230","in 1176":"1176","1243":"1243","1176":"1176","1230":"1230","vers 1243":"environ 1243","Europa":"Europe","lifeSummary":"Gauthier Desprest de Quiévrain est né en 1176, à Europe. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Isabeau de Mortagne de Tournai. Il est décédé environ 1243, à l’âge de 68 ans."},"de":{"in 1176–vers 1243":"1176–um 1243","1176–Female":"1176–Verstorben","1230–Male":"1230–Verstorben","1176–1243":"1176–1243","ABT 1230":"um 1230","in 1176":"1176","1243":"1243","1176":"1176","1230":"1230","vers 1243":"um 1243","Europa":"Europa","lifeSummary":"Gauthier Desprest de Quiévrain wurde 1176 in Europa geboren. Er hatte mit Isabeau de Mortagne de Tournai mindestens 1 Sohn. Er starb um 1243 im Alter von 68 Jahren."},"ht":{"in 1176–vers 1243":"1176–ab